WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.000
Hi everybody, my name is Zach Verham. I am an engineer on the Connect team, and I'm really excited to give this workflow demo today.

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:18.000
We're going to be talking about a new feature in Connect that we're really excited about called OAuth Integrations.

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:28.000
And what this is, is it allows published apps on Connect to interact with third-party resources using the app viewer's OAuth credentials.

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:36.000
And so we're going to talk over the course of this workflow demo about what this feature is, and why we're so excited about it,

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:43.000
and what it allows you to do in the new usage patterns in Connect that this opens up.

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:50.000
We're going to talk about how to set up fine-grained access controls in Databricks Unity Catalog.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:01:01.000
And then we're going to show an application that makes use of this new feature in Connect to use the fine-grained access controls that we set up in Databricks

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:11.000
when querying data to get unique personalized views of that data in applications that are published to Connect.

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:20.000
And we're going to talk a little bit near the end about what the developer experience is, and how to begin using this feature in your own applications.

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:29.000
It's important to call out, we're going to show this feature as it interacts with Databricks, but this same pattern will also work with Snowflake.

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:35.000
And we'll have time at the end after the demo for Q&A.

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:49.000
So really briefly, Posit Connect, for those of you who are unfamiliar, it's a way, it facilitates being able to publish and share various data science artifacts,

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:57.000
whether those are static content like a Querta document, or interactive applications like a Shiny app.

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:05.000
And this feature specifically works with interactive content, so like a Shiny or a Streamlit or a Dash app.

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:20.000
And it is designed and built to make it easier to interact with the data that you might have in your Databricks environment or your Snowflake environment.

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:30.000
So it's important to call out here, the way that customers and users would try to implement this type of interaction previously,

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:42.000
is that you would set perhaps environment variables that are using service account like credentials to interact with resources like Databricks or Snowflake.

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:58.000
So the problem that this flow ran into pretty quickly is that these deployments really only have one identity that they're using when they're interacting with the external resource.

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:09.000
So having fine grained access control that respects, say, how different users or user personas might interact with that external resource would be really, really difficult.

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:19.000
Some of the workarounds that people would use would be maybe deploying the same content item with either different business logic,

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:30.000
where it's running different queries against the dataset, or perhaps different service account credentials to interact with that external resource as a different account identity.

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:35.000
But this means that you're deploying the same content over and over and over.

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:49.000
And it's the responsibility of the app to ensure that data is being accessed securely and that the permissions that are applied to a given user are being respected.

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:59.000
So this moves the locus of sort of secure access out of the data source and into the applications that are querying that data.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:12.000
So what this new feature supports is that where in Databricks Unity Catalog, for example, you can set up fine grained row and column based access control,

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:20.000
and you can set up like really robust access protocols against those data sources.

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:31.000
It's now possible to deploy content to connect that transparently relies on what is set up on top of the data in one centralized location.

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:39.000
So you can deploy a single application to connect, which serves many users and many different data access patterns.

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:47.000
And the app is transparently relying on what the security protocol is at the data source itself.

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:56.000
So in this workflow demo, we're going to set up a data source with fine grained access controls in Databricks Unity Catalog.

00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:05.000
And then we're going to show how those permissions can then be delegated to connect using this new OAuth integrations feature.

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:08.000
So let's go ahead and jump over to Databricks.

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:16.000
So this is our Databricks workspace, and we are going to use this example Lending Club data set.

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:25.000
So this is a table that contains a lot of information about various mortgage loans that were obtained through the Lending Club platform.

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:29.000
And so we can see there's a lot of information here.

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:39.000
And we can notice that there are a couple of columns that seem like they might contain sensitive information, perhaps personally identifiable information.

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:43.000
So in this case, we're looking at this.

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:49.000
This column has information about the employment information about the loanee.

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:56.000
And there might be some information about their annual income that maybe we don't want everybody in our organization to be able to access.

00:05:56.000 --> 00:06:01.000
And similarly, this data is running across the United States.

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:08.000
So maybe there are certain people who in our organization who should only access certain subsets of the data.

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:16.000
It's possible to set these restrictions in Databricks itself using column masks and row filters.

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:19.000
So we're going to look at one of each of those.

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:25.000
So if I jump over here, we can see that we have a mask function already set up.

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:32.000
And what this is doing is it is checking to see who the current user is who's querying the data.

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:45.000
And we are saying in this mask that if the current user is the demo Databricks user, then instead of returning the data itself, we're going to mask it out with a star.

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:47.000
So we're not going to actually return that data.

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:52.000
We're going to return this star string instead.

00:06:52.000 --> 00:07:00.000
We also have a row filter that is going to do a similar sort of check against the current user.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:03.000
And we're checking to see if it's this demo Databricks user account.

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:10.000
And if it is, then we are going to check the zip code column of the loan table.

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:13.000
And we're going to see if it has this nine or an eight in it.

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:19.000
And what this is doing is it's checking to see if it's a zip code on the western side of the United States.

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:26.000
So we have our two filter mask functions set up.

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:32.000
We're now going to really easily apply them to our lending club data set.

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:36.000
And these are just really simple SQL commands.

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:41.000
So we're going to alter these columns where we think that this data might be sensitive.

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:44.000
And we're going to set the demo mask to apply to those columns.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:50.000
And we're going to also alter the table and set a row filter that is going to look at the zip code column

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:57.000
and potentially filter out to just the western region depending on who the current user is.

00:07:57.000 --> 00:08:02.000
So the end result of these filters is that our demo Databricks user cannot see any columns

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:05.000
that would be considered personally identifiable information.

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:12.000
It can only see a subset of the data related to loans from the western region of the United States.

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:20.000
So we have our data set up and we have our access control set up in Databricks itself.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:25.000
And so now we want to create some content and we want to publish some content to Connect

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:30.000
that is going to use these fine grained credentials.

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:33.000
So I already have this app deployed up to Connect.

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:36.000
I'm going to jump over to it.

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:44.000
And I'm actually going to hit the content directly so that way you can see what the login flow looks like

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:48.000
as a viewer who's coming in to interact with the app for the first time.

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:54.000
So if I go to this content URL, what you're going to see is I'm going to be automatically redirected

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:58.000
to go through an OAuth login flow against Azure.

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:02.000
And I'm going to log in and be logging in as myself.

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:05.000
So I'm going to go ahead and hit that URL.

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:09.000
So I get taken to an Azure login. I'm going to pick my account.

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:12.000
I'm going to be taken through this login flow.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:15.000
And the end result is I'm going to be taken back to Connect.

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:20.000
And Connect is going to then have my OAuth access token.

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:29.000
And now the content is able to request the access token from Connect and use it to query data from Databricks.

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:34.000
So you can see here that the app is aware of who I am.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:40.000
And it is querying that same data set that we just looked at in the Unity catalog

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:44.000
and doing some aggregations and visualizations with it.

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:49.000
We know that from our column mask and our row filter,

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:53.000
I did not have any restrictions in my ability to access this data.

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:55.000
So I'm able to see everything.

00:09:55.000 --> 00:09:59.000
I can see the columns that we said are personally identifiable.

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:04.000
I can see every region. I have access to the whole data set.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:09.000
And this looks very similar to how you might set up this sort of interaction with Databricks

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:16.000
using service account-like credentials, which was the pattern that most people used previously.

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:23.000
And a quick aside here, I do have this same application with the same source code running locally.

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:26.000
And we can see that it behaves the exact same way.

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:32.000
We put a lot of thought into what the developer experience is like with this feature.

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:40.000
And we really wanted to make sure that the app would run the same way on your local laptop

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:44.000
as you're building it, as it would when it is being published up to Connect,

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:48.000
that the same code works in both environments.

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:51.000
And so it's the same source code running both on Connect and locally.

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:57.000
And we can see that I'm able to query the data as myself.

00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:01.000
And I'm getting the full data set from the Unity catalog.

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:04.000
And I want to jump over really quick to show how that's working

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:11.000
and how you can begin to build these apps for yourself.

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:17.000
So we have these cookbook examples that are going to be published later this week

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:21.000
that show how you can set up integrations with Databricks and Snowflake.

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:27.000
And it is really, really easy to get this set up and to get going.

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:29.000
So this is not the exact same code.

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:36.000
This is a constrained simplified example that just shows how in a few lines of code,

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:40.000
you can get this working in your own applications.

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:47.000
So all you need to do ultimately is there is this session token

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:51.000
that's associated with the viewer that you'll get out of the header

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:54.000
that's being passed into your app.

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:59.000
And the actual way of getting the header is going to vary

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:02.000
depending on the framework that you're using.

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:05.000
So this is how you do it in Shiny.

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:07.000
I'm actually going to jump over and show how to do it in Streamlet

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:12.000
because that's what is running up on the Connect server that I'm showing.

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:14.000
But you can see that it's really, really similar.

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:17.000
There's a slight change in the syntax of how to get the header,

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:21.000
but the code ultimately looks very, very similar.

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:27.000
And this Posit credential strategy comes out of the Posit SDK.

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:30.000
And you can see that it is accepting that session token

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:33.000
that's identifying the user who's interacting with the content.

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:36.000
And it's also accepting a local strategy.

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:39.000
And what this allows us to do is we can determine

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:42.000
whether the app is running locally on your laptop

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:44.000
or if it's running up on a Connect server.

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:49.000
And if it's running locally, we can fall back to the Databricks CLI

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:56.000
sort of native way of authenticating with your Databricks workspace.

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:59.000
So that means that the code is able to run

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:05.000
and do sort of the personalized view of the data knowing who I am,

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:09.000
whether it's running locally or up on Connect.

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:12.000
So once we build this credential strategy,

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:16.000
we pass that into a Databricks SDK config.

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:20.000
And once we have that, we're able to make queries against the API.

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:23.000
And we can make very specific queries

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:29.000
that identify the user who's actually making that request.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:34.000
And similarly, it's very easy to then pass this into a SQL connector

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:38.000
where we can begin to run queries against the Unity catalog itself.

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:43.000
And those queries are going to respect the row

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:48.000
and column level access control that we set up previously.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:51.000
So I've shown how this is working as me.

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:53.000
I've shown data that looks pretty much the same

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:55.000
as what you would see from a service account.

00:13:55.000 --> 00:13:59.000
But I think where you can really see how powerful this feature is

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:02.000
is if I jump over to an incognito window

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:05.000
where I'm logged in as a different user.

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:09.000
So here I'm actually logged in as that demo Databricks user

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:15.000
that we applied the masks and the filters for in the Unity catalog.

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:22.000
And we can see that this user is not seeing the same data that I'm seeing.

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:27.000
Specifically, this user is only seeing the West region.

00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:30.000
And they are seeing that column mask that we applied

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:36.000
where it's starring out the data that is personally identifiable.

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:40.000
And you can really see the power of this if I put them side by side

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:45.000
where you can see that there are materially different views of the data

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:50.000
in both views where the aggregations are ultimately different

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:53.000
because the users are receiving different data.

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:56.000
But we can see that this is the same application.

00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:00.000
It's the same code running on Connect.

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:04.000
And it is presenting different views of the data in Databricks

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:11.000
depending on the user who is logged in and interacting with the app.

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:14.000
So this is, I think, very exciting.

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:18.000
I think it is going to open up a lot of new usage patterns on Connect

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:21.000
and a lot of new ways of interacting with third-party resources

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:25.000
like Databricks and Snowflake.

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:36.000
And one last thing I want to show is if I hop over to the Connect server

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:40.000
and look at the integrations that are available.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:45.000
And these are integrations that your Connect admin would set up for the server

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:49.000
for all published content to potentially be able to use.

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:53.000
We currently have native support for Databricks and Snowflake.

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:56.000
We also support just an Azure OAuth integration.

00:15:56.000 --> 00:15:59.000
And we also support a custom integration.

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:06.000
So any external OAuth app we support integrating with

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:12.000
and using this flow to do viewer-based access against that third-party resource.

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:16.000
So anything that implements OAuth we can potentially communicate with

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:18.000
and people can build apps against.

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:20.000
And that's really, really exciting.

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:25.000
We are going to continue to add to this list of integrations that we support natively.

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:29.000
This is something that we want to continue to expand.

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:32.000
And we're really excited to see how people use this feature

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:36.000
and the types of things that it's going to open up.

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:38.000
So thank you so much for your time.

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:41.000
And I think we're going to jump over to Q&A now.

